{"id":"1806.11042","submitter":"Ludovico Lami","authors":"Ludovico Lami, Krishna Kumar Sabapathy, Andreas Winter","title":"All phase-space linear bosonic channels are approximately Gaussian\n  dilatable","comments":"33 pages, 2 figures; v2 has a simplified proof of one of the main\n  results, Theorem 8","journal-ref":"New J. Phys. 20:113012, 2018","doi":"10.1088/1367-2630/aae738","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph math-ph math.MP","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We compare two sets of multimode quantum channels acting on a finite\ncollection of harmonic oscillators: (a) the set of linear bosonic channels,\nwhose action is described as a linear transformation at the phase space level;\nand (b) Gaussian dilatable channels, that admit a Stinespring dilation\ninvolving a Gaussian unitary. Our main result is that the set (a) coincides\nwith the closure of (b) with respect to the strong operator topology. We also\npresent an example of a channel in (a) which is not in (b), implying that\ntaking the closure is in general necessary. This provides a complete resolution\nto the conjecture posed in Ref. [K.K. Sabapathy and A. Winter, Phys. Rev. A\n95:062309, 2017]. Our proof technique is constructive, and yields an explicit\nprocedure to approximate a given linear bosonic channel by means of Gaussian\ndilations. It turns out that all linear bosonic channels can be approximated by\na Gaussian dilation using an ancilla with the same number of modes as the\nsystem. We also provide an alternative dilation where the unitary is fixed in\nthe approximating procedure. Our results apply to a wide range of physically\nrelevant channels, including all Gaussian channels such as amplifiers,\nattenuators, phase conjugators, and also non-Gaussian channels such as additive\nnoise channels and photon-added Gaussian channels. The method also provides a\nclear demarcation of the role of Gaussian and non-Gaussian resources in the\ncontext of linear bosonic channels. Finally, we also obtain independent proofs\nof classical results such as the quantum Bochner theorem, and develop some\ntools to deal with convergence of sequences of quantum channels on continuous\nvariable systems that may be of independent interest.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 28 Jun 2018 15:47:46 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 13 Nov 2018 11:34:40 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-11-14"}
